observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor ensure that the provisions of Sections 344 and 347 of R.A. No. 7160 on certification/approval of DVs and rendition of accounts; Sections 4.5 and 4.6 of P.D. No. 1445 on disbursement of funds and complete documentation; and Section 7.2.1(a) of COA Circular No. 2009-006 on submission of reports and supporting documents to the Auditor are strictly adhered in all transactions of the Municipality.

Municipal Accountant:

prepare and maintain GLs and SLs for all cash accounts and immediately submit to the Audit Team the required subsidiary schedule of GL balances of cash accounts for all funds and SLs per depository bank; 

dutifully observe the prompt preparation and submission of monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements to the Audit Team, including the bank statements and valid bank debit/credit advices,  for verification purposes to ascertain the correctness of the Cash in Bank account balance in compliance with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 96-011; 

exercise caution in analysing financial transactions, closely monitor and strengthen review of JEVs, CkDJ/CDJ/GJ and GLsto ensure that all financial transactions are properly and accurately captured and taken up in the books to prevent the frequent occurrence of accounting errors and inaccurate and misleading information as they would materially affect the accuracy and fair presentation of account balances in the financial statements; 

review the previous accounting entries affecting the cash accounts to identify the causes of negative CLT account balance and effect the necessary correcting entries duly supported with sufficient documentation including a satisfactory explanation therefor; and 

submit to the Audit Team the lacking documentary requirements for disbursements totalling ₱9,749,622.74  such as copies bank statements and paid checks.

Properly record payments of on-going projects under the CIP account pursuant to Section 50 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume I to reflect in the financial statements the infrastructure projects of the agency which are still under construction;

Reclassify the CIP account to the appropriate PPE account as soon as the project is completed;

Maintain CIP ledger cards for each project to monitor the amount paid per billing of the contractor in case of construction by straight contract and the amount paid for materials, labor and overhead in case of construction by administration; and

Identify the details of the dormant balance of CIP account and trace pertinent documents to support the transfer to the completed PPE account and other necessary adjustments in the books.

a. 	Require the concerned officials and employees to provide justification on various claims on pump boat/shuttle hire and hotel accommodations and immediately submit the lacking supporting documents. Otherwise, subject transactions shall be suspended and/or disallowed in audit;

b. 	Propose budget for the purchase of additional watercrafts in the ensuing year, which is specifically intended to ferry officials and employees from the official station to their destination and vice-versa to lessen the cost of traveling expenses incurred for pump boat hire;

c. 	Instruct the ICO-Municipal Accountant to thoroughly review the disbursements or liquidation vouchers, as part of the internal audit system of the Municipality to determine completeness of supporting documents, compliance of claims with applicable laws, rules and regulations on travel and correctness of computations, before recording the same in the books of accounts;

d. 	Ensure that the provisions of COA Circular Nos. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and 96-004 dated April 19, 1996 and Executive Order No. 298 dated March 23, 2004 are strictly complied with; and

e. 	Exercise prudence in approving travel orders and itineraries.

Strictly adhere with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its revised IRR and GPPB Resolution No. 09-2009 dated November 23, 2009 in all government procurement;

Perform thorough review and evaluation of the legality of the alternative mode of procurement before resorting to shopping and small value procurement. Preparation of PPMP and APP must be strictly complied;

Conduct rigid screening of eligibility of suppliers and contractors and update the compilation of the suppliers, contractors and consultants shortlist; and

Discontinue the practice of paying through cash advances the procurement of construction materials for infrastructure projects and strictly adhere to the requirement that all payments must be made by check and directly paid to the suppliers, contractors, dealers and creditors.

We recommended that the ICO-Municipal Accountant:
a. Strictly observe the monthly preparation of Bank Reconciliation Statements to determine the correct balance of the Cash in Bank account in the financial statements, in compliance with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996;
b. Exert diligent effort in reconciling the book and bank balances on a timely basis and submit the Bank Reconciliation Statements and other relevant documents showing that the identified reconciling items were properly recorded and adjusted in the books of accounts;
c. Request from the depository bank the concerned copies of Credit and Debit Memos to determine their validity and effect the necessary adjustments;
d. Communicate with banks for all reconciling items which still need verification; and
Reconcile accounting records with the cash book of the ICO-Municipal Treasurer. Henceforth, both offices should reconcile their records regularly so that errors or discrepancies that may be noted could be readily adjusted.

We reiterated that:
a. The Municipal Mayor should enjoin all concerned officials and employees to strictly adhere with the rules and cash advances. (Section 3.3.2(a) of COA Circular No. 96-004 dated April 19, 1996);
b. The ICO-Municipal Accountant should cause the immediate withholding of salaries and other claims of those officers and employees who have failed to settle cash advances for travel and other purposes, as well as the institution of other sanctions, pursuant to Sections 5.1.3 and 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002. The ICO-Municipal Accountant is authorized to “delete the name of the official or employee from the subsequent payrolls until such time that the travel cash advance has been fully liquidated.” (Section 16 of Executive Order No. 248 and Section 3.3.2(b) of COA Circular No. 96-004 dated April 19, 1996);
c. After expiration of the prescribed period, the ICO-Municipal Accountant should cause the immediate withholding of salaries and other claims of those officers and employees who have failed to settle cash advances for travel and other purposes, as well as the institution of other sanctions, pursuant to Sections 5.1.3 and 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002. The ICO-Municipal Accountant is authorized to “delete the name of the official or employee from the subsequent payrolls until such time that the travel cash advance has been fully liquidated.” (Section 16 of Executive Order No. 248 and Section 3.3.2(b) of COA Circular No. 96-004 dated April 19, 1996);
d. The ICO-Municipal Accountant, ICO-Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Mayor should refrain from signing cash advance vouchers and obligation requests of officials and employees with unliquidated balances; and
Management should initiate the filing of the request for write-off from the Commission on Audit pertaining to the outstanding balance of deceased employees.

We recommended that the ICO-Municipal Accountant to:
a. Properly record payments of on-going projects under the CIP account pursuant to Section 50 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1 to reflect in the financial statements the infrastructure projects of the agency which are still under construction;
b. Reclassify the CIP account to the appropriate PPE account as soon as the project is completed;
c. Maintain CIP ledger cards for each project to monitor the amount paid per billing of the contractor in case of construction by straight contract and the amount paid for materials, labor and overhead in case of construction by administration; and
d. Identify the details of the dormant balance of CIP account and trace pertinent documents to support the transfer to the completed PPE account and other necessary adjustments in the books.

We recommended for the Municipal Mayor to:
a. Require the concerned officials and employees to provide justification on various claims on pump boat/shuttle hire and hotel accommodations and immediately submit the lacking supporting documents. Otherwise, subject transactions shall be suspended and/or disallowed in audit;
b. Propose budget for the purchase of additional watercrafts in the ensuing year, which is specifically intended to ferry officials and employees from the official station to their destination and vice-versa to lessen the cost of traveling expenses incurred for pump boat hire;
c. Instruct the ICO-Municipal Accountant to thoroughly review the disbursements or liquidation vouchers, as part of the internal audit system of the Municipality to determine completeness of supporting documents, compliance of claims with applicable laws, rules and regulations on travel and correctness of computations, before recording the same in the books of accounts;
d. Ensure that the provisions of COA Circular Nos. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and 96-004 dated April 19, 1996 and Executive Order No. 298 dated March 23, 2004 are strictly complied with; and
e. Exercise prudence in approving travel orders and itineraries.

We recommended that Management:
a. Strictly adhere with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its revised IRR and GPPB Resolution No. 09-2009 dated November 23, 2009 in all government procurement;
b. Perform thorough review and evaluation of the legality of the alternative mode of procurement before resorting to shopping and small value procurement. Preparation of PPMP and APP must be strictly complied;
c. Conduct rigid screening of eligibility of suppliers and contractors and update the compilation of the suppliers, contractors and consultants shortlist; and
d. Discontinue the practice of paying through cash advances the procurement of construction materials for infrastructure projects and strictly adhere to the requirement that all payments must be made by check and directly paid to the suppliers, contractors, dealers and creditors.

We recommended that the Municipality:
a. Reclassify the special trust fund balance of B5.456,884.93 by debiting “Due to LGUs” and crediting “Trust Liability- DRRM?” in the Trust Fund books;
b. Immediately transfer the CY 2015 unexpended balance of 21,578,387.95 to a special trust fund, pursuant to Section 5.1.10 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012;
c. Create a separate depository account solely for the unexpended balance of the LDRRM in the special trust fund to avoid possible misuse of the fund, pursuant to Section 310 of R.A. No. 7160; and
d. Strictly observe the provisions of the said COA Circular on the immediate transfer of the unexpended balance at year-end and proper recording of transactions under the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund.

We recommended that the ICO-Municipal Accountant to record on-going projects under the CIP account pursuant to Section 50 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume I to reflect in the financial statements the infrastructure projects of the agency which are still under construction;
Maintain CIP ledger cards for each project to monitor the amount paid per billing of the contractor in case of construction by straight contract and the amount paid for materials, labor and overhead in case of construction by administration;
Identify the details of the dormant balance of CIP account and trace pertinent documents to support the transfer to the completed PPE account and other necessary adjustments in the books; and
Reclassify the CIP account to the appropriate PPE account as soon as the project is completed.
Management Comment:
During the audit exit conference, the Municipal Accountant commited to identify the projects lodged in the non-moving CIP account and close the same to the appropriate PPE accounts.

We reiterated that:
The Municipal Mayor should enjoin all concerned officials and employees to strictly adhere with the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, as provided for under COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
The ICO-Municipal Accountant should closely monitor unsettled cash advances of each officers and employees and send within ten (10) days before the expiration of the prescribed period, a written reminder under the signature of the head of agency or his duly authorized representative, enjoining officials or employees concerned, including those that are separated from service, to immediately liquidate their cash advances. (Section 3.3.2(a) of COA Circular No. 96-004 dated April 19, 1996);
After expiration of the prescribed period, the ICO-Municipal Accountant should cause the immediate withholding of salaries and other claims of those officers and employees who have failed to settle cash advances for travel and other purposes, as well as the institution of other sanctions, pursuant to Sections 5.1.3 and 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002. The ICO-Municipal Accountant is authorized to “delete the name of the official or employee from the subsequent payrolls until such time that the travel cash advance has been fully liquidated.” (Section 16 of Executive Order No. 248 and Section 3.3.2(b) of COA Circular No. 96-004 dated April 19, 1996);
The ICO-Municipal Accountant, ICO-Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Mayor should refrain from signing cash advance vouchers and obligation requests of officials and employees with unliquidated balances; and
Management should initiate the filing of the request for write-off from the Commission on Audit pertaining to the outstanding balance of deceased employees as provided for under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.
Management Comment:
During the audit exit conference, the Management  committed to adhere strictly to the audit recommendations.
